## What happened

.NET 11 removed the managed/OpenSSL-backed DSA fallback on macOS. Apple's native crypto framework (Security.framework) has **never** supported DSA, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on that platform. On Linux and Windows, native DSA support still exists, so those builds continue to work.

This follows the deprecation trajectory that started with `SYSLIB0030` (DSA marked obsolete).

## How to fix it

**Option A — Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must keep verifying legacy DSA signatures):**

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)
{
    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is a pure managed implementation — works on all platforms regardless of native crypto support.

**Option B — Migrate to a modern algorithm (best long-term):**

If you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, which are supported natively on all three platforms and are not deprecated.

**Option C — Runtime guard (short-term shim):**

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // native path
}
else
{
    // BouncyCastle fallback
}
```

### Recommendation

If the library only *verifies* existing legacy signatures and can't change the signing algorithm, go with **Option A**. If you own the full pipeline, plan a migration to ECDSA/Ed25519 (**Option B**).
